              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Wikipedia explains Euler's Identity as an equation that shows the profound connection between key mathematical constants. It is expressed as:\n\n\\[ e^{i\\pi} + 1 = 0 \\]\n\nHere:\n- \\( e \\) is Euler's number, the base of natural logarithms (\\( \\approx 2.718 \\)).\n- \\( i \\) is the imaginary unit (\\( i^2 = -1 \\)).\n- \\( \\pi \\), the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter (\\( \\approx 3.14159 \\)).\n\nEuler's Identity is a special case of Euler's Formula, which relates complex exponentials to trigonometric functions:\n\n\\[ e^{i x} = \\cos(x) + i \\sin(x) \\]\n\nSetting \\( x = \\pi \\), the formula simplifies to \\( e^{i\\pi} = -1 \\), and adding 1 results in \\( e^{i\\pi} + 1 = 0 \\).\n\nThe identity is celebrated for its beauty in mathematics due to its simplicity and connection among five fundamental constants (0, 1, \\( \\pi \\), \\( e \\), and \\( i \\)) and operations (addition, multiplication, exponentiation, and equality).",
